Part I - Exploration on Ford GoBike System Data¶

by Andrés Martínez¶

Introduction¶

This data set includes information about individual rides made in a bike-sharing system covering the greater San Francisco Bay area.

This dataset contains information on 183412 bike trips carried out during the month of february in the year 2019.

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

The dataframe consist of 183412 rows (one for each ride) and 16 columns.

In the columns we have information on the following variables:

  • duration_sec: trip duration in seconds
  • start_time: date and time of the start of the trip
  • end_time: date and time of the end of the trip
  • start_station_id: each station has a unique number id. These are the start station id
  • start_station_name
  • start_station_latitude
  • start_station_longitude
  • end_station_id
  • end_station_name
  • end_station_latitude
  • end_station_longitude
  • bike_id: each bike has a unique number of identification
  • user_type: indicates whether the user is a 'Suscriber' or a 'Customer
  • member_birth_year
  • member_gender
  • bike_share_for_all_trip

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

In this dataset we can find interesting information on:

  • Trip typical durations
  • Typical distances covered on trips
  • Use of the service during the week
  • Identifying bike rush hours
  • Most popular stations
  • Study the use of the service by age
  • Study the use of the service by gender
  • Number of trips by user type
  • Relation between the incoming and outgoing bikes in every station

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

The following features will help support this investigation:

  • Durations
  • Date and time
  • Members gender
  • User type
  • Start and end stations
  • Members year of birth
  • Stations latitude and longitude

For our analysis we want to add a new column with the distance covered in the trip. We will calculate such distance using the Haversine formula. The function below taken to calculate this formula has been taken from here

In [55]:
def haversine(lon1, lat1, lon2, lat2):
    '''This function applies Haversine formula and returns the value in meters'''
    
    lon1 = np.radians(lon1.astype(float))
    lat1 = np.radians(lat1.astype(float))
    lon2 = np.radians(lon2.astype(float))
    lat2 = np.radians(lat2.astype(float))

    r = 6371000
    
    
    dlon = np.subtract(lon2, lon1)
    dlat = np.subtract(lat2, lat1)

    a = np.add(np.power(np.sin(np.divide(dlat, 2)), 2),
               np.multiply(np.cos(lat1),
                           np.multiply(np.cos(lat2),
                                       np.power(np.sin(np.divide(dlon, 2)), 2))
                           )
              )
    c = np.multiply(2, np.arcsin(np.sqrt(a)))

    return c*r

# We drop columns in the initial dataframe

For each station we calculate the sum of the total number of start and end trips as a measure of popularity of the station. Also we want to have a measure of bike availability on each station. To do so, we will calculate a coeficient which takes into account the number of outgoing bikes divided by the incoming bikes. The formula we will use is the following:

$\text{Availability coefficient} = 1 - \frac{\text{outgoing bikes}}{\text{incoming bikes}}$

This way, positive values indicate that the number of incoming bikes is bigger than the outgoing bikes; negative values indicate that the number of outgoing bikes is bigger than the incoming; and values close to zero mean that there is a balance between incoming and out going bikes.

In [61]:
# We count for each station the number of trips starting and ending 
start_counts = df_clean.start_station_id.value_counts().sort_index()
end_counts = df_clean.end_station_id.value_counts().sort_index()

# We count the popularity of stations by the total number of trips starting and ending in that station
station_popularity = start_counts + end_counts

# We create a coeficient which takes into account the number of outcome trips divided by the income trips
# This is a measure of bike availability on each station
start_end_ratio = start_counts/end_counts
bike_availability_coef = 1 - start_end_ratio

# We store this information in columns in our stations dataframe
df_stations['bike_availability_coef'] = bike_availability_coef
df_stations['station_popularity'] = station_popularity

# We create a function to plot the percentage on a vertical bar countplot
def print_percentage(data, column_name: str, order, x_shift = 0.2):
    '''
    This function is to be used below a count plot. 
    It prints the percentage on the bars of vertical countplots
    '''

    val_counts = data[column_name].value_counts().loc[order]
    total_counts = val_counts.sum()

    max_count = val_counts.sort_values(ascending=False).iloc[0]

    for i, count in enumerate(val_counts):
        pct_string = f'{100*count/total_counts:.1f}%'
        plt.text(i - x_shift, count + 0.02 * max_count, pct_string, va='center')

It seems that the number of trips is higher during weekdays and lower during weekends. Lest'us look deeper into it.

In order to analyce the use of bike rental on the different days of the week, we will label dates by day of the week. And also we create a label for ordinary weekdays and weekend days. Then we will plot a barchart for the use on every day of the week.

In [77]:
# We create the new columns in our dataframe
df_clean['day_week'] = 0
df_clean['weekend'] = 'Ordinary'

# We associate week days to dates
fr = np.arange(1, 28, 7)
sa = np.arange(2, 28, 7)
su = np.arange(3, 28, 7)
mo = np.arange(4, 28, 7)
tu = np.arange(5, 28, 7)
we = np.arange(6, 28, 7)

# We create the labels
for i in np.arange(1, 29, 1):
    
    # We create the datetime intervals by days
    start = dt.datetime(2019, 2, i)

    if i != 28:
        end = dt.datetime(2019, 2, i + 1)
    else:
        end = dt.datetime(2019, 3, 1)
        
    idx = df_clean[(df_clean['start_time'] > start) & (df_clean['start_time'] < end)].index
    

    if i in fr:
        df_clean['day_week'][idx] = 'Friday'
    elif i in sa:
        df_clean['day_week'][idx] = 'Saturday'
        df_clean['weekend'][idx] = 'Weekend'
    elif i in su:
        df_clean['day_week'][idx] = 'Sunday'
        df_clean['weekend'][idx] = 'Weekend'
    elif i in mo:
        df_clean['day_week'][idx] = 'Monday'
    elif i in tu:
        df_clean['day_week'][idx] = 'Tuesday'
    elif i in we:
        df_clean['day_week'][idx] = 'Wednesday'
    else:
        df_clean['day_week'][idx] = 'Thursday'
        
# We create a class for the day of the week
days = ['Monday', 'Tuesday', 'Wednesday', 'Thursday', 'Friday', 'Saturday', 'Sunday']
dayclass = pd.CategoricalDtype(ordered=True, categories=days)
df_clean['day_week'] = df_clean['day_week'].astype(dayclass)

In [82]:
# We define a function which removes outliers

def drop_outliers_IQR(data, column_name):
   '''
   This function drops outliers from the values in a column in a dataframe and returns a copy of the dataframe without outliers.
   It drops al values outside the interval (mean - 1.5*IQR, mean + 1.5*IQR)
   Being IQR the interquartile range.
   '''
# We calculate the quartiles
   Q1 = np.quantile(data[column_name], 0.25)
   Q3 = np.quantile(data[column_name], 0.75)

# We calculate the interquartile range
   IQR = Q3 - Q1


# We calculate the mean value
   mean = np.mean(data[column_name])

# We find and drop outliers
   out_idx = data[(data[column_name] < mean - 1.5 * IQR) | (data[column_name] > mean + 1.5 * IQR)].index
   data_without_outliers = data.drop(index=out_idx)
   return data_without_outliers
In [83]:
# We create a dataframe without outliers in duration and distance
df_clean_out = drop_outliers_IQR(df_clean, 'distance_meters').reset_index(drop=True)
df_clean_out = drop_outliers_IQR(df_clean_out, 'duration_sec').reset_index(drop=True)

In [88]:
# We create a function to take samples from a dataframe
def random_sample(data, n, seed = 0):
    '''This function takes a random sample from a dataframe
    data: Dataframe, n: size of the sample'''
    assert n < data.shape[0], 'n must be smaller than the number of rows of the dataframe'
    np.random.seed(seed)
    sample_idx = np.random.choice(data.shape[0], n, replace=False)
    return data.loc[sample_idx]

Conclusions¶

In this exploration, after describing and cleaning our dataset we made different kind of explorations, in this order: univariate, bivariate and multivariate explorations.

We have investigated a dataset of the Ford GoBike bike-rental service. We made different kind of explorations of the variables present in the dataframe: univariate, bivariate and multivariate explorations.

On univariate explorations we analyced: duration of trips, distances covered by trips, age of users, user types, users gender, use of the service over time and on the different week days, stations popularity and stations balance between incoming and outgoing bikes.

On bivariate explorations we analyced: distance-duration relationship, users age by day of the week, use over time on a weekday and on a day of the weekend and station popularity and bike availability relationship.

And on the multivariate exploration we made a scattermatrix on the variables distance, duration and users age, and a facet grid comparing users age and gender on a normal weekday and a day of the weekend.

Our main finding are the following:

  • We found out that the big majority of users (90.5%) are suscribers and not regular cutomers.

  • We found that stations with a low popularity are much more numerous than those with a high popularity.

  • We also analyced the balanced between incoming and outgoing bikes from stations, and we found that the majority of stations are balanced, and in the most popular stations the tendency is to have more incoming bikes than outgoing on this month, this year.

  • Ages of users, distances covered and duration of trips have an exponential decay after a maximum peak. We explored the relationship first between duration and distance covered by trips and then the relationship between these variables and the users age.

  • We found out that the number of trips is considerably lower on the weekends compared to weekdays and we found that on weekdays the number of trips during rush hours is much higher. This take us to the conclusion that this bike service is mainly used as a mean of transport to go to work, which is good explanation for other of our findings: the median age of users is lower during the weekend.

  • It was surprising to find an incredibly big difference between the number of male and female users, where male users represent the 74.6%. The age distribution of male is slightly bimodal and of female is unimodal. We found no explanation for this big difference between genders. Do women usually prefer other means of transport? If this is the case we should wonder why. Or maybe are there still less women working outside home? These questions could be approach on a different investigation.
